<subSubSection id="C3666562D2049D2A3AD4DD8EEA33FE6A" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="153" pageId="17" pageNumber="152" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2049D293AD4DD8EEC1CFB36" blockId="17.[136,629,1134,1228]" box="[136,620,1206,1228]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D6AD2049D293AD4DD8EEF07FB31" box="[136,375,1206,1227]" class="Dinophyceae" family="Peridiniaceae" genus="Glenodinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peridiniales" pageId="17" pageNumber="152" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="species" species="quadridens">
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD2049D293AD4DD8EEF07FB31" box="[136,375,1206,1227]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">Glenodinium quadridens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in J. Schiller (1935: 117)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2049D293AD4DDC2EA90FAEE" blockId="17.[136,1452,1274,1408]" box="[136,1248,1274,1301]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">Cell shape: Pentagonal, slightly compressed dorsoventrally, with bilateral symmetry in apical view.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2049D293AE1DC26EEA6FA7A" blockId="17.[136,1452,1274,1408]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">
Thecal characteristics: Tabulation, Po, 5ʹ, 1a, 7ʹʹ, 6C, 5S, 5ʹʹʹ, 2ʹʹʹʹ. Conical epitheca, longer than the hypotheca. The only anterior intercalary plate symmetrically located in the dorsal side (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD2049D293E58DC7AEA1DFAA6" box="[1028,1133,1346,1372]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[136,229,2060,2082]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,1433,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-571@17.[189,1398,1433,2036]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. Peridiniopsis quadridens. A. Epitheca plates, ventral view. B. Epitheca plates, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426109/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
). Rounded hypotheca, with spines.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF036661D2049D293AD4D134EA08F7D9" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426109" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5426109" box="[136,1144,2060,2083]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426109/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="152" startId="17.[136,229,2060,2082]" targetBox="[189,1397,1433,2036]" targetPageId="17">
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2049D293AD4D134EA08F7D9" blockId="17.[136,1144,2060,2083]" box="[136,1144,2060,2083]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD2049D293AD4D134EF78F7DB" bold="true" box="[136,264,2060,2082]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">FIGURE 11.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD2049D293B52D135EC77F7D8" box="[270,519,2061,2082]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D6AD2049D293B52D135EC73F7D8" authorityName="Bourrelly" authorityYear="1968" baseAuthorityName="F. Stein" box="[270,515,2061,2082]" class="Dinophyceae" family="Peridiniaceae" genus="Peridiniopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peridiniales" pageId="17" pageNumber="152" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="species" species="quadridens">Peridiniopsis quadridens</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD2049D293850D134EC54F7DB" bold="true" box="[524,548,2060,2081]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">A.</emphasis>
Epitheca plates, ventral view. 
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD2049D293915D135ED2FF7D8" bold="true" box="[841,863,2061,2082]" pageId="17" pageNumber="152">B.</emphasis>
Epitheca plates, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2079D2A3AE1D9A6EF74FF26" blockId="18.[136,1451,158,401]" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">
Cingulum and sulcus: Cingulum slightly displaced, descendent. The sulcus penetrates slightly in the epitheca (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD2079D2A3ACCD9FAEE88FF26" box="[144,248,194,220]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[136,229,2060,2082]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,1433,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-571@17.[189,1398,1433,2036]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. Peridiniopsis quadridens. A. Epitheca plates, ventral view. B. Epitheca plates, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426109/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2079D2A3AE1D9DEEC83FEFA" blockId="18.[136,1451,158,401]" box="[189,755,230,256]" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">
Locality: Guatapé reservoir North-west 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D2079D2A3821D9DEEC9FFEFA" box="[637,751,230,256]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">Colombia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2079D2A3AE1D832EDA0FE96" blockId="18.[136,1451,158,401]" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">
Comments: This is the first record of the species in 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D2079D2A395AD832ED08FEDE" box="[774,888,266,292]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. Measurements and detailed diagnostic characters were not possible to perform, due to the low number of specimens found. Identification was based on the presence of five apical plates and a single anterior intercalary plate in one empty theca.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D2079D2A3AE1D84EEA33FE6A" blockId="18.[136,1451,158,401]" box="[189,1091,374,401]" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">
World distribution: Europe, 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D2079D2A3BA4D84EEC43FE6A" box="[504,563,374,400]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">USA</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D2079D2A3832D84FED74FE6A" box="[622,772,374,401]" name="New Zealand" pageId="18" pageNumber="153">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D2079D2A394ED84EEA47FE6A" author="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J." box="[786,1079,374,400]" pageId="18" pageNumber="153" refId="ref16007" refString="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J. (2018) Susswasserflora von Mitteleuropa. 6. Dinophyceae. B. Budel, G. Gartner, L. Krienitz &amp; M. Schagerl (Eds.) Springer, Berlin, 561 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 662 - 56269 - 7 _ 7" type="book" year="2018">Moestrup &amp; Calado 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
